<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Gensler v. crypto</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commi=
ssion is not in the general investor-protection business. If someone comes =
to you and offers you a can=E2=80=99t-lose opportunity to buy=C2=A0Florida =
swampland, and it turns out they=E2=80=99re lying, the SEC will not get inv=
olved. If they sell you fake gold coins or forged Picassos, the SEC will no=
t get involved. If they lie to you in the course of selling you complicated=
 commodity futures contracts, the SEC will not get involved. (The Commodity=
 Futures Trading Commission will.)=C2=A0The SEC is in the business of prote=
cting investors in=C2=A0<em>securities</em>. If someone comes to you and of=
fers you a can=E2=80=99t-lose opportunity to buy stock in a cannabis compan=
y, and it turns out they=E2=80=99re lying,=C2=A0<em>then=C2=A0</em>the SEC =
will get involved.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine a narr=
ow, minimalist SEC approach, one that says something like =E2=80=9Cif peopl=
e lie to you while trying to sell you stock in some crazy company, the SEC =
will go after them, but other than that you=E2=80=99re on your own.=E2=80=
=9D But in fact that has never been the SEC=E2=80=99s approach. For many de=
cades now, the SEC =E2=80=94 and U.S. securities law generally =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0has taken a pretty expansive view of what a =E2=80=9Csecurity=E2=80=9D i=
s. The famous case is=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/24648563.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvU0VDX3YuX1=
cuX0ouX0hvd2V5X0NvLg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB828b6f10" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">SEC v. W.J. Howey Co.</a>, wh=
ere the Supreme Court almost=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>rule that a can=E2=80=
=99t-lose investment opportunity=C2=A0in Florida swampland counts as a secu=
rity. Technically the land was citrus groves, and the land itself wasn=E2=
=80=99t a security, but an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=80=9D where some=
one else harvested the oranges for you was. All sorts of things in the worl=
d might not be securities, but organized=C2=A0<em>investment opportunities=
=C2=A0</em>in those things will turn out to be securities. Or at least the =
SEC will argue that they are.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CCryp=
to=E2=80=9D is a very broad category of stuff,[1] loosely united by the fac=
t that people mostly buy the stuff hoping that it will go up and make them =
rich. This does not by itself make everything in crypto a security! Not eve=
rything that people buy hoping it will go up is a security subject to SEC j=
urisdiction. But, you know, most things. Certainly when a brand-new categor=
y of stuff appears in the world, and its principal purpose is for people to=
 buy it hoping that it will go up, the SEC is going to take an interest.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/24648563.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdz=
L3B1YmxpYy1zdGF0ZW1lbnQvZ2Vuc2xlci1hc3Blbi1zZWN1cml0eS1mb3J1bS0yMDIxLTA4LTA=
z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB807dffae" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">a speech that SEC Chair Gary Gensler gave yester=
day</a> about crypto. It is short and nontechnical and I do not think it sa=
ys anything new or=C2=A0surprising or even really interesting, but it has g=
otten a lot of attention because it=E2=80=99s Gensler=E2=80=99s first real =
policy statement about crypto. Gensler=E2=80=99s most recent job before bec=
oming SEC chair was, like, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/24648563.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjEtMDgtMDMvd2lsbC1nb3Zlcm5tZW50LXJlZ3VsYXRlLWNyeXB0by1zZWMtY2hhaXItZ=
2FyeS1nZW5zbGVyLW9uLWJpdGNvaW4tYW5kLW92ZXJzaWdodA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
6906e5fd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 being a professor of crypto at MIT</a>, so I suppose some people might hav=
e expected him to be=C2=A0pro-crypto. But Gensler also has previous experie=
nce=C2=A0in government running the CFTC, where he gained a reputation for b=
eing=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>pro-regulatory, so I certainly expected him to=
 be pro-regulation of crypto. (Which, at the SEC, is roughly synonymous wit=
h =E2=80=9Canti-crypto.=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And=
 this speech is very pro-regulation, which means specifically that it very =
much comes down on the side of concluding that lots of crypto things, thing=
s that are in gray areas, things that are not really analogous to any exist=
ing categories of traditional securities, are securities. Here is Gensler=
=E2=80=99s overview of the situation:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The SEC has a three-part mission =E2=80=94 to protect investors, fac=
ilitate capital formation, and maintain fair, orderly, and efficient market=
s in between them. We focus on financial stability as well. But at our core=
, we=E2=80=99re about investor protection.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
If you want to invest in a digital, scarce, speculative store of value, tha=
t=E2=80=99s fine. Good-faith actors have been speculating on the value of g=
old and silver for thousands of years.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Righ=
t now, we just don=E2=80=99t have enough investor protection in crypto. Fra=
nkly, at this time, it=E2=80=99s more like the Wild West.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">This asset class is rife with fraud, scams, and abuse in cer=
tain applications. There=E2=80=99s a great deal of hype and spin about how =
crypto assets work. In many cases, investors aren=E2=80=99t able to get rig=
orous, balanced, and complete information.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
If we don=E2=80=99t address these issues, I worry a lot of people will be h=
urt.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might read all of tha=
t and say =E2=80=9Csure, fine, but what does this have to do with the SEC?=
=E2=80=9D The SEC is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>about =E2=80=9Cinvestor protect=
ion=E2=80=9D broadly; it is about investor protection=C2=A0<em>from scammy =
securities</em>. If <em>bad</em>-faith actors speculate on the value of gol=
d, the SEC can=E2=80=99t really stop them, because gold is not a security. =
The fact that crypto is rife with scams does not mean that the SEC has to a=
ddress it; the SEC has to address it only if it is rife with=C2=A0<em>secur=
ities=C2=A0</em>scams.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gensler argues =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0or at least asserts =E2=80=94=C2=A0that it is. But he is biased=
: He runs a regulatory organization, he is interested in crypto, he doesn=
=E2=80=99t like scams, so he wants to use his regulatory power to crack dow=
n on crypto scams. He might be tempted to expand that power, to treat borde=
rline gray-area things as securities and crack down on them, even if they a=
ren=E2=80=99t really securities.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now,=
 I should say that, separately, I think that Gensler is right. Most of the =
things that he worries about=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>probably securities und=
er existing U.S. law. But I=E2=80=99m biased too; I was trained as a securi=
ties lawyer. Certainly there are people who are biased the other way, who t=
hink that crypto is an interesting sandbox for financial innovation that is=
=C2=A0<em>different=C2=A0</em>from existing categories, and that preemptive=
ly treating everything as a security and subjecting it to SEC regulation wi=
ll stifle innovation.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway after that int=
roduction Gensler moves on to a list of crypto things that he wants to regu=
late. He starts with initial coin offerings. It has long been accepted at t=
he SEC that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/246485=
63.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktM=
TAtMTQvdGhlLXNlYy1yZWFsbHktZG9lc24tdC1saWtlLWljb3M/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B75e7941a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> most ICOs are securities</a>. I basically agree. But we have stopped real=
ly talking about ICOs around here, because the SEC position that ICOs are s=
ecurities pretty much meant the end of the ICO market, at least in the U.S.=
 If you want to raise money for a project by offering crypto tokens for cas=
h, the SEC will say that you are doing a securities offering and make you r=
egister it and file financial statements and so forth. The ICO market was b=
asically a way to raise money=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>doing that, and th=
e SEC crackdown kind of ended it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this =
is not without controversy. ICO tokens often looked a lot like other forms =
of corporate currency =E2=80=94=C2=A0frequent-flyer miles, gift cards, etc.=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0that are obviously not securities. Regulating ICO tokens as=
 securities sometimes felt like a stretch: These things did not really look=
 like securities, and it was not obvious that they were under the SEC=E2=80=
=99s jurisdiction. (In fact SEC Commissioner Hester Peirce <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24648563.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMzAvd291bGQteW91LWJvcnJvd=
y1mcm9tLXRoZS1mZWQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe54b8bbb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> argued as much</a>.) On the ot=
her hand, tons of them were really scammy. It made sense for the SEC to get=
 involved, as a general investor-protection matter. But that did stretch ou=
t the boundaries of what crypto things count as securities.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Next Gensler moves on to decentralized finance platforms. =
I think it=E2=80=99s pretty obvious that a lot of DeFi lending platforms, a=
utomated market maker contracts, etc., are securities, and I <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24648563.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjEvamFtaWUtZGltb24tZ29=
0LWEtYm9udXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB44bef301" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> have</a> <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24648563.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDMvYW1jLWhhcy1hLWJpdC1tb3JlLXN0b2Nr=
LXRvLXNlbGw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2ffb7f3f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> said</a> that the SEC will come after=
 them. Gensler does not exactly get into the argument, but he clearly has s=
ome=C2=A0plans for those platforms:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The American public is buying, selling, and lending crypto on these tr=
ading, lending, and DeFi platforms, and there are significant gaps in inves=
tor protection.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Make no mistake: To the ext=
ent that there are securities on these trading platforms, under our laws th=
ey have to register with the Commission unless they meet an exemption.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Make no mistake: If a lending platform is offer=
ing securities, it also falls into SEC jurisdiction.</p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One important point here =E2=80=94=C2=A0not a point =
made by Gensler, but one that will be important in regulation of lending pl=
atforms =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that a lending platform can offer securities even=
 if the underlying=C2=A0<em>cryptocurrency=C2=A0</em>is not a security. So,=
 while many crypto things are arguably securities,=C2=A0<em>Bitcoin itself=
=C2=A0</em>is not a security. But a lending platform that says =E2=80=9Chey=
 put your Bitcoins into this pool and we will give you a 10% return on them=
=E2=80=9D probably=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>offering a security, or at least t=
hat is the position taken by the SEC (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/24648563.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDMvYW1jLWhhcy1hLWJpdC1tb3JlLXN0b2NrLXRvLXNlbG=
w/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC2ffb7f3f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> against BitConnect</a>) and New Jersey regulato=
rs (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24648563.26595=
0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjEva=
mFtaWUtZGltb24tZ290LWEtYm9udXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC44bef301" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> against BlockFi</=
a>). It is the same basic concept as Howey: Florida orange groves are not a=
 security, but a pooled profit-seeking investment in those groves is a secu=
rity; Bitcoin is not a security, but a pool of Bitcoins managed by someone =
seeking profitable investments is.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(O=
ne other important point, not discussed by Gensler, is whether a pool of Bi=
tcoins managed=C2=A0<em>by a smart contract=C2=A0</em>is a security. I thin=
k this is an interesting question! A smart contract that seeks to make mone=
y through a transparent, open-sourced trading/lending algorithm arguably=C2=
=A0<em>isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>the sort of =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=
=80=9D covered by Howey, because investors are not relying on the efforts o=
f a manager to make a profit, but on the deterministic=C2=A0operation of co=
de. Also, even if it is a security, who is selling it? Who do you sue? Here=
 is where I think you get into territory that is genuinely different from e=
xisting securities, where you really do have a novel question of whether th=
e SEC has jurisdiction. But my guess is that the SEC will think it does.)</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Next, stablecoins. A <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24648563.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjIvcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZmlybS1n=
b3QtcmljaC1tYWtpbmctcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZmlybXMtcmljaA/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBefaf44c2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> collateralized stablecoin</a> is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/24648563.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDktMDQvcHV0LXRoZS1tb25leS1mdW5kLW9uLXRoZS1ibG9ja=
2NoYWlu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa5055135" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> basically a money market fund</a>, money =
market funds are regulated by the SEC and their shares are securities, so t=
he SEC naturally wants to treat stablecoins as securities and regulate them=
. I am less convinced that this view is correct,[2] but it=E2=80=99s probab=
ly the SEC=E2=80=99s view; here is Gensler:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">These stablecoins also may be securities and investment compan=
ies. To the extent they are, we will apply the full investor protections of=
 the Investment Company Act and the other federal securities laws to these =
products.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What about a non-col=
lateralized, algorithmic stablecoins? These are not pooled investments in c=
ommercial paper; they are just digital tokens meant to represent a dollar. =
Yet there are =E2=80=A6=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/24648563.265950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTcvdGl0YW5pdW0tZ290LWNydXNoZWQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB6157b7e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> obvious investor-protection problems</a> there too? You could take the v=
iew =E2=80=9Ca collateralized stablecoin is a money market fund and therefo=
re=C2=A0a security, while an algorithmic stablecoin is a=C2=A0money market =
fund=C2=A0with no money in it, and therefore a much worse security.=E2=80=
=9D[3]=C2=A0I do not quite know what theory the SEC could use to regulate a=
lgorithmic stablecoins, but I look forward to finding out.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Etc. The speech is not exhaustive, and I am perhaps wrong i=
n interpreting it to mean =E2=80=9Ceverything in crypto is a security until=
 proven otherwise.=E2=80=9D But I do think that=E2=80=99s the basic thrust =
of it. Meanwhile not every regulator agrees; after Gensler=E2=80=99s speech=
, Republican CFTC Commissioner Brian Quintenz <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
