=E2=80=99t want it to be used on hacks that are=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>big,=
 because then you will attract unwanted attention and bring down the full f=
orce of the U.S. government on you. You have to vet your targets carefully.=
 And ransomware seems to work largely on a franchising model, where groups =
like BlackMatter mostly build software that is then deployed by independent=
 licensees, so you have to vet your <em>clients</em> carefully too. You wan=
t to provide your software to=C2=A0<em>criminals</em>, sure, but you need t=
o screen the criminals to make sure that they are competent and ambitious, =
but not too ambitious. It is all=C2=A0<em>sort of=C2=A0</em>like a normal c=
ompany. And sort of not.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway the i=
nterview spends a lot of time on these sorts of compliance-function questio=
ns:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>[Dmitry Smilyanets]=
: Most recently, the largest groups=E2=80=94DarkSide, REvil, Avaddon, BABUK=
=E2=80=94have disappeared from the scene. Many researchers believe that thi=
s was due to the attention of the top leadership of the United States and R=
ussia to the situation with ransomware attacks. Is it true? Do you think yo=
ur product will have the same fate?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">[BlackMatter]: Yes, we believe that to a large extent their exit from the=
 market was associated with the geopolitical situation on the world stage. =
First of all, this is the fear of the United States and its planning of off=
ensive cyber operations, as well as a bilateral working group on cyber exto=
rtion. We are monitoring the political situation, as well as receiving info=
rmation from other sources. When designing our infrastructure, we took into=
 account all these factors and we can say that we can withstand the offensi=
ve cyber capabilities of the United States. For how long? Time will tell. F=
or now, we are focusing on long-term work. We also moderate the targets and=
 will not allow our project to be used to encrypt critical infrastructure, =
which will attract unwanted attention to us. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;"><strong>DS: I have already seen several recruiting announcements for =
your team. How many penetration testers would you like to recruit? Is it ea=
sier to work with a small but strong team, or with an army of script kiddie=
s?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BM: We are geared at strong, se=
lf-sufficient teams with experience, their own technical solutions, and a r=
eal desire to make money, not someone who wants to try the business out. We=
 usually filter out script kiddies before they get access to our admin pane=
l. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>DS: What do you think =
about the attacks carried out against Colonial Pipeline=E2=80=99s infrastru=
cture or JBS? Does it make sense to attack such large networks?</strong></p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BM: We think that this was a key factor for t=
he closure of REvil and DarkSide, we have forbidden that type of targeting =
and we see no sense in attacking them.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">But there is also a certain amount on just the nuts and bolts of r=
ansomware design:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>DS: A=
re you planning to add new features to the product, following the example o=
f StealBit?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BM: Yes, the software =
is constantly being improved, in terms of the new functions that will appea=
r in the near future=E2=80=94printing the text of the note on all available=
 printers. We also watch our competitors and always implement what we consi=
der promising and in demand by our clients.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">If you seize control of a company=E2=80=99s computers and enc=
rypt all of its files, you have to=C2=A0<em>tell=C2=A0</em>the company that=
 you=E2=80=99ve done that. A pop-up message on every screen saying =E2=80=
=9Chahaha we locked your files, send us Bitcoin=E2=80=9D is useful, but pri=
nting a similar message=C2=A0on every printer on the network is a good redu=
ndancy? I don=E2=80=99t know, I am not an expert in ransomware user-experie=
nce design, but the point is that these guys are. That is just a thing that=
 you can be an expert in, and there is a competitive market for good ransom=
ware design.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also here=E2=80=99s a good que=
stion with a good answer:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><stro=
ng>DS: Obviously, there are many talented professionals on your team. Why i=
s it that this talent is aimed at destructive activities? Have you tried le=
gal penetration testing?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BM: We do=
 not deny that business is destructive, but if we look deeper=E2=80=94as a =
result of these problems new technologies are developed and created. If eve=
rything was good everywhere there would be no room for new development.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is one life and we take everything from =
it, our business does not harm individuals and is aimed only at companies, =
and the company always has the ability to pay funds and restore all its dat=
a.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have not been involved in legal=
 pentesting and we believe that this could not bring the proper material re=
ward.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I can=E2=80=99t fault th=
e logic. Why do you use your hacking talents for crime, rather than legally=
 helping companies identify and eliminate vulnerabilities? Well, see, crime=
=C2=A0<em>pays better</em>. =E2=80=9CThere is one life and we take everythi=
ng from it.=E2=80=9D</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0"=
 cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
